														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1829095">
									

<blockquote>
<p>its eyes are fixed directly on the lens, this time looking not at the subject but the person viewing the video feed.</p>
</blockquote>
<blockquote>
<p>It is not staring at the subject; rather it is fixated on the camera lens, giving the illusion it is making eye contact with those viewing the footage.</p>
</blockquote>
<blockquote>
<p>the face comes in full view of the camera, eye contact being made directly with the viewer.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>I am sorry<sup class="footnoteref"><a id="footnoteref-981200-1" href="javascript:;" class="footnoteref" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnote-981200-1')">1</a></sup> but this is a deal breaker for me. This just seems so, so, out of place? So unprofessional? So amateur? &quot;It's staring into the camera, not at the camera, but at the person who is viewing the camera. Locking eye contact with its pupil-less eyes and reading your soul for cookie recipes.&quot; It was all fun and creepy until these bits. (well, that and everyone's amazing guesses at the distance of the crying child voice echoing up from a bottomless stairwell) I get that it's a creepy idea, that it's looking through the camera to see you, you who felt so safe sending people down without risk to yourself, but this is trying too hard. With paintings you will often get the feeling that person's eyes are following you. They do not actually follow you, and anyone who gets that feeling should remember that. Staring into the camera, verses staring into the eyes of the person who viewed the recording, how do you even note that? Not like this is all I know.</p>
<p>/bitching</p>
